  "prompt": "What is the average age of PhD graduates by discipline?",
  "response": "The average age of PhD graduates can vary significantly by discipline, field of study, and country, as well as individual circumstances such as the time taken to complete undergraduate and master's degrees, research progress, and other personal factors.\n\n### General Trends by Discipline:\n1. **STEM Fields (Science, Technology, Engineering, Mathematics):**\n   - PhD graduates in STEM fields often complete their degrees earlier than those in other disciplines due to the structured nature of these programs and the emphasis on younger researchers.\n   - Average age: **Late 20s to early 30s** (e.g., 28\u201332).\n\n2. **Social Sciences and Humanities:**\n   - PhD programs in fields like history, sociology, literature, or philosophy often take longer to complete due to the nature of research, funding challenges, and the time required for fieldwork or archival work.\n   - Average age: **Mid-30s** (e.g., 33\u201337).\n\n3. **Professional Fields (e.g., Business, Law, Education):**\n   - PhDs in professional disciplines may attract older students who have already worked in their fields for several years.\n   - Average age: **Mid-30s to early 40s**.\n\n4. **Health and Medical Sciences:**\n   - PhD graduates in medical or health-related fields may vary widely in age, depending on whether they pursue the degree immediately after a medical degree or later in their careers.\n   - Average age: **Early to mid-30s**.\n\n### Factors Influencing Age:\n- **Time to Complete the Degree:** Humanities and social sciences PhDs often take longer (e.g., 6\u20138 years or more) compared to STEM fields (e.g., 4\u20136 years).\n- **Prior Experience:** Some students enter PhD programs after gaining work experience, which can increase the average age.\n- **Country-Specific Trends:** In some countries, PhD programs are entered directly after a bachelor's degree, while others require a master's degree first.\n\n### Data Sources:\nTo get precise figures, consulting national statistics (e.g., the U.S. National Science Foundation\u2019s Survey of Earned Doctorates or similar reports from other countries) would provide detailed insights by discipline.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
